FILL_CH25 = {
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>Festus's arrival in Caesarea and immediate trip to Jerusalem initiates the final sequence of Paul's Roman custody — the Christological journey toward Rome that the risen Christ himself mandated in 23:11 ('you must testify also in Rome'). Each new provincial governor who inherits Paul's case becomes an unwitting instrument of Christ's mission-plan. The Christological sovereignty is working through the bureaucratic machinery of Roman provincial administration to move Paul inexorably to the capital.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The chief priests and leaders of the Jews formally press their case against Paul before the new governor — the Christological pattern of institutional religious power mobilizing against the gospel's witness. The same coalition that prosecuted Jesus before Pilate now pursues his chief apostle before Festus. The Christological parallel is structural: the high-priestly establishment, unable to destroy the Christological mission through its own courts (ch. 22-24), now appeals to Roman authority, just as they did at Golgotha.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The request that Paul be transferred to Jerusalem — with an ambush planned to kill him on the road — is the Christological pattern of religious persecution dressed in legal process. The leaders know Roman courts will not convict Paul on theological grounds, so they plan extra-judicial assassination. The Christological protection: the same risen Christ who warned Paul in 23:11 will frustrate this plan through Festus's Roman instinct to keep the prisoner in his own custody. Divine providence works through Roman administrative protocol.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Festus's counter — 'Paul was being kept at Caesarea and that he himself was about to depart shortly' — is the providential protection of the Christological mission through bureaucratic procedure. Festus has no knowledge of the ambush and no theological stake in the outcome; he simply follows Roman practice in keeping the prisoner at his own administrative seat. The risen Christ's protection of his witness does not require supernatural intervention — it works through the ordinary workings of imperial administration that God has established.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Festus's invitation for the Jewish authorities to come down and accuse Paul 'if there is anything wrong about the man' — the Christological test set in formal judicial terms. The question 'is there anything wrong?' will be answered consistently throughout the trial sequence: no, there is nothing criminally wrong. Every Roman official who examines Paul reaches the same conclusion. The Christological innocence of the apostolic mission is vindicated not by the church's testimony but by the empire's own legal judgment.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The formal trial at Caesarea — Festus on the judgment seat, Paul brought before him — parallels the trial of Jesus before Pilate on a judgment seat (John 19:13). The Christological pattern repeats: the apostle of the crucified-and-risen Lord faces the same judicial structure that condemned his Lord. The parallel is not accidental in Luke's narrative; it demonstrates that the apostolic community participates in Christ's own passion pattern. What happened to the head happens to the body.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Jews from Jerusalem surrounding Paul with 'many and serious charges that they could not prove' — the Christological mission faces accusation without substance. The charges are serious in rhetoric but empty in evidence, exactly as the charges against Jesus were (Luke 23:14 — Pilate's verdict: 'I find no guilt in this man'). The Christological community is consistently charged with what it has not done; the inability to prove the charges is the legal form of the risen Christ's vindication.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Paul's triple defense — no offense against the law of the Jews, the temple, or Caesar — is the Christological claim of innocence on all three relevant jurisdictions. The Christological mission does not violate Torah (it fulfills it), does not desecrate the temple (Christ is the true temple), and does not commit treason against Caesar (the kingdom of God and Roman civic order are not in direct conflict). The risen Christ's apostle is innocent by the standards of every court that has jurisdiction to try him.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Festus's question — 'Do you wish to go up to Jerusalem and there be tried before me on these charges?' — is the Christological crisis point: the governor is willing to place Paul in the ambush zone for political advantage ('to do the Jews a favor'). The Christological protection comes not through miraculous intervention but through Paul's own Roman citizenship rights. The risen Christ has given his apostle legal tools (citizenship, the right of appeal) precisely for this moment. The political maneuvering that threatens becomes the occasion for the Caesar-appeal that fulfills the mission-mandate.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Paul's declaration — 'I am standing before Caesar's tribunal, where I ought to be tried' — is the Christological confidence of one who knows where the divine plan is going. Paul doesn't appeal to Caesar as a desperate escape; he invokes the Christological necessity of reaching Rome (23:11). The Roman legal system, with all its imperfections, is the providential vehicle through which the risen Christ moves his witness from Jerusalem to the empire's center. 'I ought to be tried here' — the <em>dei</em> (ought) echoes the divine necessity that runs through Luke-Acts.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Paul's appeal — 'I appeal to Caesar' — is the Christological pivot of the entire Acts narrative. The appeal to Caesar (the right of every Roman citizen to have capital cases heard by the emperor) is simultaneously a legal maneuver and a Christological fulfillment: God had told Paul in 23:11 that he must testify in Rome. The legal mechanism and the divine mandate converge. The risen Christ uses Roman law to accomplish what his sovereignty had already determined. The appeal to Caesar is Paul's 'Yes' to the divine necessity that has been driving the entire narrative toward Rome.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Festus's ruling — 'To Caesar you have appealed; to Caesar you will go' — is the moment when human judicial decision coincides with divine mission-plan. Festus makes a purely procedural Roman decision; the risen Christ's purpose is accomplished through it. The Christological pattern: God's sovereign will works through human decisions, including the decisions of officials who have no awareness of participating in the fulfillment of divine purpose. The kingdom of God advances through the kingdoms of the world without the world knowing it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Agrippa II and Bernice's arrival in Caesarea introduces the last and most theologically sophisticated of Paul's hearers before the journey to Rome. Agrippa is a Herodian king with genuine knowledge of Jewish Scripture and tradition — the audience ideally positioned to understand Paul's Christological argument from the OT. The Christological mission is about to encounter the Jewish royal court; the risen Christ's case will be argued before someone who cannot plead ignorance of the prophetic testimony.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Festus's presentation of Paul's case to Agrippa — describing a prisoner left by Felix — begins the Christological testimony to the highest Jewish authority available in the Roman east. The risen Christ is orchestrating a hearing before a Jewish king; the Christological argument from Scripture, which Paul will deploy in ch. 26, requires exactly this kind of audience. Festus doesn't understand the theological substance but accurately identifies that Paul's case centers on disputed Jewish religious questions.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The high priests' demand for a condemnatory verdict — 'asking for a sentence against him' — is the Christological accusation's final form before the highest available Jewish authority. The chief priests want death; Paul's proclamation of the risen Christ is the specific offense. The Christological significance: the institutions of Jewish religious leadership consistently demand the death of those who proclaim the resurrection of Jesus, just as they demanded the death of Jesus himself. The apostolic pattern of suffering mirrors the messianic pattern.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Festus's explanation of Roman legal principle — 'it was not the custom of the Romans to give up anyone before the accused met the accusers face to face' — is the Christological mission's legal protection articulated as Roman due-process. The risen Christ is providentially protected by Roman legal custom that requires evidence and confrontation. The very empire that crucified Jesus now, through its legal procedures, repeatedly protects Jesus's apostle from execution. The Christological irony runs through the entire trial sequence in Acts.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Festus's swift judicial action — sitting on the tribunal 'without delay' the next day — is the Roman administrative efficiency that serves the Christological mission. The risen Christ's witnesses are not left in indefinite procedural limbo; the legal process moves forward. The Christological sovereignty works through the promptness of a Roman governor who simply wants to dispatch a bureaucratic problem. Every administrative decision that moves Paul's case forward moves the Christological mission toward Rome.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Festus's summary — 'When his accusers stood up, they brought no charge in his case of such evils as I supposed' — is the Roman official's acknowledgment that the case against Paul is theologically rather than criminally framed. The Christological proclamation does not constitute a criminal offense by Roman standards. The 'evils I supposed' suggests Festus expected charges of sedition or violence; what he got was a theological dispute. The Roman legal system repeatedly makes this finding: the gospel is legally innocent even when religiously controversial.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Festus's diagnosis — 'they had certain points of dispute with him about their own religion and about a certain Jesus, who was dead, but whom Paul asserted to be alive' — is the most precise secular summary of the Christological claim in the NT. A Roman governor, with no theological stake and no framework for resurrection, accurately identifies the dispute's center: a dead man Paul claims is alive. The resurrection claim is the Christological skandalon that makes no sense to the Roman mind but is the entirety of Paul's gospel. 'A certain Jesus, dead, whom Paul asserts to be alive' is the gospel in a sentence.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Festus's puzzlement — 'being at a loss how to investigate these questions' — is the Christological claim's confrontation with a mind that has no category for bodily resurrection. The Roman governor is not theologically hostile (unlike the high priests) but genuinely bewildered: the dispute is about something that falls outside Roman legal and philosophical frameworks. The Christological claim always transcends the epistemological frameworks of the cultures it enters; the resurrection is not derivable from prior categories but requires new categories to understand.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Paul's appeal to be kept for 'the decision of the emperor' is the Christological mission's Roman legal mechanism reaching its final destination. The 'emperor' (Augustus, the Sebastos — the revered one) is the highest human court; Paul is invoking the empire's ultimate judicial authority. The risen Christ is sovereign over that authority too: the emperor who will hear Paul's case is, unknowingly, an instrument in the Christological mission to fill Rome with the gospel's proclamation. The appeal to human supremacy serves the proclamation of divine supremacy.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Agrippa's desire — 'I would like to hear the man myself' — is the Christological invitation the risen Christ has arranged. Agrippa's curiosity opens the door for the most theologically sophisticated speech in Acts. The king who knows the Jewish scriptures, the prophets, and the messianic traditions will hear Paul's argument from within his own world of reference. The Christological proclamation always seeks the hearing of those best positioned to understand its scriptural grounding; Agrippa is the ideal Jewish audience for the OT Christological argument.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The great pomp of Agrippa's entrance — 'with great pomp, with military tribunes and prominent men of the city' — is the Christological reversal the gospel enacts: the king who enters with military and civic pageantry sits before a prisoner in chains, but the prisoner holds the word of life that the king needs. The Christological counter-narrative to worldly power is always present in Acts' trial scenes: the wealth and authority on the judgment seat is less significant than the testimony of the prisoner who knows the risen Christ. The kingdom of God reverses every evaluation of greatness.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Festus's formal introduction — 'All the Jewish people petitioned me about him in Jerusalem and here, crying out that he ought not to live any longer' — frames the Christological mission as a life-or-death conflict with the existing religious order. The mob's demand for Paul's death (paralleling the mob's demand for Jesus's death before Pilate in Luke 23:18) is the measure of the Christological threat the gospel poses to the established order. The risen Christ's witnesses provoke exactly the response that Christ himself provoked: the cry for elimination from those whose identity is threatened.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Festus's personal verdict — 'I found that he had done nothing deserving death' — is the Roman governor's declaration of Christological innocence. This is the third such Roman innocence verdict in Acts' trial sequence (Felix, 24:22-23; Festus here; Agrippa will add his own in 26:31-32). The triple Roman declaration of innocence mirrors the triple Pilate declaration in Luke's passion (23:4, 14, 22). The Christological pattern: the Roman state repeatedly declares the innocence of Christ's witnesses, just as it repeatedly declared the innocence of Christ himself.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Festus's dilemma — 'I have nothing definite to write to my lord about him' — reveals the Christological mission's unique status: legally innocent, religiously controversial, theologically incomprehensible to its Roman judges. The Christological claim cannot be reduced to a Roman legal category. The governor who must write a letter to the emperor about a prisoner whose case he cannot frame has inadvertently identified the gospel's transcendence of all human judicial frameworks. The risen Christ cannot be categorized by the empire's existing categories — his lordship creates new ones.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Festus's problem — 'it seems to me unreasonable, in sending a prisoner, not to indicate the charges against him' — is the administrative awkwardness that opens the door for Paul's hearing before Agrippa. The Christological mission proceeds through bureaucratic necessity: a governor who needs help framing a letter convenes a hearing that becomes the occasion for the most comprehensive Christological proclamation in Acts. The risen Christ turns an administrative inconvenience into a Christological opportunity. Every obstacle in Acts becomes an opening for the gospel.</p>"
  }
}

FILL_CH26 = {
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>Agrippa's invitation — 'You are permitted to speak for yourself' — is the Christological opportunity Paul has been providentially positioned to receive. The raised hand is the orator's gesture; Paul is about to deliver not merely a legal defense but a comprehensive Christological testimony to a Jewish king who knows the scriptures. The risen Christ has arranged this hearing: from the Damascus road to the Jerusalem temple to the Caesarean prison to this moment, every step of Paul's journey has been directed toward this testimony before the highest available Jewish authority.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Paul's opening thanksgiving — 'I consider myself fortunate that it is before you, King Agrippa, I am going to make my defense today' — is the Christological confidence of one who knows that the argument from Scripture requires exactly this kind of audience. Agrippa's expertise in 'all the Jewish customs and controversies' makes him the ideal judge for the Christological case; he cannot plead ignorance of the messianic hope or the prophetic testimony. Paul's Christological argument will be aimed at a listener who has every intellectual resource needed to evaluate it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Paul's appeal for patient hearing ('I beg you to hear me patiently') signals that the Christological argument will be substantial and cumulative. The defense is not a brief legal statement but a comprehensive Christological autobiography: Paul's life from Pharisaic formation through conversion through mission is one continuous Christological narrative. The Christological claim requires narrative to convey; it cannot be reduced to a proposition without losing its persuasive force. Paul needs time because the risen Christ's story, as it intersects with his own, requires time to tell.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Paul's appeal to his publicly-known life — 'known by all the Jews ... from the beginning' — grounds the Christological testimony in verifiable biography. The Christological proclamation is not a private mystical claim but a public history that witnesses can evaluate. Paul's pre-conversion life is known; the contrast with his post-conversion life makes the Christological transformation undeniable. The risen Christ's power is demonstrated precisely through the radical change in a publicly known individual — the before-and-after of Paul's life is the Christological argument from experience.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Paul's identification as a Pharisee — 'according to the strictest party of our religion I have lived as a Pharisee' — is the Christological foundation of his argument. His Pharisaic identity is not an embarrassment but an asset: Pharisees believe in the resurrection of the dead. Paul's Christological claim (Jesus rose from the dead) is the specific fulfillment of the general Pharisaic hope he held before his conversion. He is not abandoning Jewish theology but declaring its fulfillment in a specific person. The Christological transition from Pharisaism to apostleship is continuous, not contradictory.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'I stand here on trial because of my hope in the promise made by God to our fathers' — the Christological argument's first thrust: Paul's trial is about Israel's own hope, not a foreign religion. The 'promise to the fathers' is the Abrahamic-Davidic-prophetic promise structure that the OT carries throughout: seed, land, blessing, Messiah, resurrection. Paul is on trial for believing that this promise has been fulfilled. The Christological claim is not the abandonment of Jewish hope but its arrival; those who reject Paul are rejecting the fulfillment of what they claim to hope for.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'To which our twelve tribes hope to attain, as they earnestly worship night and day' — the Christological claim is the content of all Israel's worship and hope. The twelve tribes' night-and-day devotion is oriented toward the hope of resurrection and messianic fulfillment; Paul's gospel declares that hope fulfilled. The Christological significance: Paul is not introducing a new religion but declaring the answer to the prayer that Israel has been praying for centuries. The irony is total — he is being accused by the very people whose deepest hope he is announcing as fulfilled.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Why is it thought incredible by any of you that God raises the dead?' — the Christological question that cuts to the center of the dispute. The resurrection of Jesus is not philosophically impossible for those who believe in the God of Israel; the Creator who gave life can restore it. The Christological skandalon for Greeks is the bodily particularity of resurrection; for Jewish objectors (other than Sadducees) the skandalon is the identification of the risen one as a crucified criminal. Paul is pressing his audience: your own theology has room for resurrection — the question is only whether this particular resurrection happened.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Paul's confession of his pre-conversion opposition — 'I myself was convinced that I ought to do many things in opposing the name of Jesus of Nazareth' — is the Christological autobiography's dark center. His persecution was not irreligious but hyper-religious: done in the name of Torah-faithfulness and temple-purity. The Christological lesson: the most dangerous opposition to Christ often comes from sincere religious conviction that has not yet encountered the risen Lord. Paul's pre-conversion state is the warning about religious zeal that has never been broken by the Christological revelation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Paul's persecution activities — imprisoning saints, casting his vote for their death, punishing them — are the Christological shadow that gives his testimony its weight. The one who imprisoned the saints is now the imprisoned saint. The one who voted for death is now the one against whom death is demanded. The Christological reversal in Paul's own biography is the enacted parable of the resurrection: what was done to Christ (death demanded, life taken) is done to his community, and what God did to Christ (vindication, life restored) is done to his community through the gospel's continuing advance.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'I tried to make them blaspheme' — the Christological goal of Paul's persecution was to force believers to deny Christ's name. The blasphemy would have been the renunciation: 'Jesus is cursed' (cf. 1 Cor 12:3, the test by which the Spirit's presence is known). Paul's former work was the systematic attempt to unravel the Christological confession; his current work is the proclamation of that confession before kings. The Christological transformation is maximal: from forcing denials to making declarations, from persecuting the name to being imprisoned for it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The setting of the Damascus road encounter — 'with authority and commission from the chief priests' — establishes the official character of Paul's pre-conversion mission. He was not a freelance zealot but a commissioned agent of the highest religious authority. The Christological significance: the risen Christ interrupted not a private journey but an official mission, deflecting the institutional power of the high-priestly establishment. The Damascus road is the risen Christ's counter-commission: the one sent by the chief priests becomes sent by the Lord of the church.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The light brighter than the sun at midday — the Christological theophany exceeds natural light. The risen Christ's glory outshines the Mediterranean noon sun; the Damascus road encounter is not a vision or dream but a reality that transcends ordinary sense experience. The Christological significance: the glorified Christ, the 'Sun of Righteousness' (Mal 4:2), the true Light that the world was made through (John 1:3-4), appears in a form that overwhelms Paul's natural perception and leaves him prostrate on the ground.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The voice in Hebrew/Aramaic — 'Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me?' — is the Christological identification of Christ with his community. The Hebrew address ('Saul') is intimate, in his own mother-tongue; the risen Christ meets Paul in his own cultural identity. 'It is hard for you to kick against the goads' — Paul has been fighting against the Christological current that has been working in him; his resistance has been painful to himself as well as destructive to others. The risen Christ's first word to his future apostle is a question that exposes the futility of resisting the direction of divine grace.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The self-disclosure — 'I am Jesus whom you are persecuting' — is the risen Christ's definitive self-identification to the one who will become his greatest interpreter. 'I am Jesus' (<em>Egō eimi Iēsous</em>): the divine 'I am' formula, the historical name, the specific person who was crucified. Not a principle, not an angel, not a vision, but Jesus — the same Jesus whose followers Paul was imprisoning, whose name Paul was trying to eliminate. The Christological identification of Christ with his persecuted community is now stated in the first person to the persecutor himself.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The commission — 'Rise and stand upon your feet, for I have appeared to you for this purpose' — is the Christological call that converts Paul's prostrate helplessness into apostolic standing. The risen Christ has not appeared to destroy Paul but to deploy him: 'to appoint you as a servant and witness.' The Christological appointment is irresistible and irreversible; Paul cannot return to his former mission once the risen Christ has claimed him. The appearance itself is the commission; the commission is the content of the appearance. The risen Christ's encounters with his servants are always simultaneously revelatory and vocational.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Delivering you from your people and from the Gentiles' — the Christological protection promised at the commission's outset. The risen Christ is not naive about the resistance Paul will face; he pre-announces the deliverance from both Jewish and Gentile opposition. The Christological sovereignty over Paul's mission extends to protection from the very forces that will try to silence it. The promise of deliverance is not a promise of safety from suffering (Paul will suffer abundantly) but a promise that the Christological mission will not be permanently stopped by human opposition.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The commission's content — 'to open their eyes, so that they may turn from darkness to light and from the power of Satan to God' — is the Christological Servant-mission. The language of opening blind eyes (Isa 42:7), turning from darkness to light (Isa 9:2; 42:6; 49:6), and transferring from Satan's power to God's — these are the Servant of Isaiah's commissioning language, now transferred to Paul as the extension of Christ's Servant mission. The Christological servant sends a servant; the light-bearing Servant (Isa 49:6) sends Paul to bear light to nations. The forgiveness and 'place among those who are sanctified' is the Christological inheritance that the Servant's sacrificial work provides.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'I was not disobedient to the heavenly vision' — the Christological obedience that defines Paul's entire apostolic career. The Damascus road was not a religious experience that Paul could file away; it was the risen Christ's direct commission that demanded immediate and total obedience. The Christological vocation is inherently imperative: the appearance of the risen Lord creates an obligation that cannot be negotiated. Paul's 'not disobedient' is the apostolic version of 'here I am, send me' (Isa 6:8) — the willing surrender of self-direction to Christological command.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Paul's mission summary — 'first to those in Damascus, then in Jerusalem, and throughout all the region of Judea, and also to the Gentiles, that they should repent and turn to God, performing deeds in keeping with their repentance' — is the Christological mission's geographic and ethical content compressed into one sentence. The sequence (Damascus → Jerusalem → Judea → Gentiles) maps onto the Acts narrative structure (9:19-30; 15:4-6; 13:1-28:31). The Christological demand of repentance-with-deeds ('performing deeds in keeping with their repentance') is not moralism but the Christological fruit that genuine conversion produces.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Because of these things, the Jews seized me in the temple and tried to kill me' — the Christological mission's first conflict with the Jerusalem temple establishment. Paul's Gentile mission (declaring the Christological light to all nations) is exactly what provoked the temple riot. The Christological irony: the temple, which was to be 'a house of prayer for all nations' (Isa 56:7; Luke 19:46), has become the place where the universal Christological proclamation is most violently opposed. Those most invested in the temple's institutions are most hostile to the Christological mission that fulfills the temple's own universal vocation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'To this day I have had the help that comes from God, and so I stand here' — the Christological sustainability of Paul's entire apostolic career is not his own resilience but divine help (<em>epikourias</em>, support from God). The risen Christ who commissioned Paul also sustains him; the mission that began with a divine encounter continues through divine assistance. The Christological confidence is not self-confidence but God-confidence: Paul stands before Agrippa not because he is strong but because the risen Christ has kept him standing through every persecution, shipwreck, imprisonment, and attempted assassination.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Festus's interruption — 'Paul, you are out of your mind; your great learning is driving you out of your mind' — is the Christological claim's reception by the rational Roman mind. Festus cannot process the resurrection claim within his philosophical framework; what falls outside his categories appears as madness. The Christological claim always exceeds the frameworks of natural human reason; the resurrection is not rationally derivable but rationally deniable by those who begin with materialist assumptions. Festus's 'madness' charge is the educated Roman's version of the Corinthian scoffing (1 Cor 1:23: 'foolishness to Gentiles').</p>",
    "25": "<p>Paul's counter — 'I am not out of my mind, most excellent Festus, but I am speaking true and rational words' — is the Christological claim's defense as coherent speech (<em>sōphrosynēs rhēmata</em>, words of soundness/sobriety). The resurrection proclamation is not irrational enthusiasm but a reasoned case based on prophetic testimony and historical events. The Christological argument is both intellectually defensible (not madness) and experientially attested (the transformation of Paul himself). The risen Christ does not demand an irrational leap of faith but a response to an evidential case that the mind can genuinely evaluate.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'The king knows about these things, and to him I speak boldly. For I am persuaded that none of these things has escaped his notice, for this has not been done in a corner' — the Christological claim's public verifiability. The events of Jesus's life, death, and resurrection happened in the public sphere of Jewish-Roman Palestine; they are not esoteric mysteries known only to initiates. Paul's address to Agrippa is an appeal to a man who has access to the historical record. The Christological confession rests on public facts that the king knows; the question is whether he will respond to them.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you believe' — the Christological argumentative move that puts Agrippa in an impossible position. If Agrippa affirms his belief in the prophets, he must contend with Paul's argument that the prophets predict exactly what Jesus fulfilled. If he denies it, he alienates his Jewish identity and authority. The Christological claim is the fulfillment of what the prophets anticipated; Agrippa's belief in the prophets is simultaneously an implicit openness to the Christological claim. Paul's rhetorical maneuver is an act of Christological evangelism — pressing the king toward the conclusion his own Scripture demands.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Agrippa's response — 'In a short time would you persuade me to be a Christian?' — is the Christological claim's nearest approach to royal assent. Whether Agrippa means this as genuine semi-conviction or as dismissal, Paul takes it seriously (v. 29). The Christological persuasion is real: the scriptural argument, the biographical testimony, the commission narrative, and the Servant-mission description have come close to moving the Jewish king. 'Almost persuaded' is the tragic form of Christological response — near enough to see the claim's force, not near enough to cross the threshold of surrender.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Paul's response — 'I would to God that not only you but also all who hear me this day might become such as I am — except for these chains' — is the Christological prayer for universal conversion without suffering. The apostle desires for his hearers not the imprisonment but the Christ who has made the imprisonment worthwhile. The Christological identity Paul wishes them to share is the risen Christ's own identity: forgiven, commissioned, sustained, heading toward a destination more certain than any throne. The chains are incidental; the Christ is everything. Paul's prayer before the royal court is pure Christological mission.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The assembly's rising — king, governor, Bernice, and those sitting with them — signals the formal end of the hearing. The Christological testimony has been given in full to the highest available earthly authority in the Roman east. The risen Christ's commission to Paul ('you will testify before kings') has been fulfilled in this courtroom. What the court does with the testimony is their own responsibility; Paul has discharged his Christological witness completely. The legal proceeding closes; the Christological effect on those present is known only to God.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The verdict in conference — 'This man is doing nothing to deserve death or imprisonment' — is the final Christological innocence declaration from the Roman-Jewish royal court. Three Roman officials (Felix's implicit finding, Festus, Agrippa) and a Jewish king have now all declared Paul's innocence. The Christological pattern reaches its climax: just as Jesus was declared innocent by Pilate, Herod, and the Roman soldiers (Luke 23:4, 14-15, 22, 47), Paul is declared innocent by every court that examines him. The apostle participates in the passion pattern; the vindication will come in the same way.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Agrippa's final word — 'This man could have been set free if he had not appealed to Caesar' — is the Christological mission's paradox: the mechanism that ensures Paul's journey to Rome simultaneously prevents his immediate release. The appeal to Caesar, which was God's instrument for moving Paul to Rome (23:11), cannot be reversed. The Christological sovereignty has locked in the trajectory: Rome is the destination, not Caesarea's freedom. The risen Christ uses even the irrevocability of Roman legal procedure to ensure that his witness reaches the empire's center. What looks like a legal trap is a Christological open door.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRIST)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH25)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH26)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'acts', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Acts mkt-christ: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
